</div><div class="news-item omega"><a href="http://news.byu.edu/archive12-oct-bridgesrain.aspx" title=""><span class="img" data-alt="Professor Brian Mazzeo tests acoustic-based measurement techniques in his la" data-src="http://home.byu.edu/home/sites/default/files/bridges.jpg"></span></a><h3><a href="http://news.byu.edu/archive12-oct-bridgesrain.aspx" title="">How highway bridges sing &ndash; or groan &ndash; in the rain to reveal their health</a></h3><p>A team of BYU engineers has found that by listening to how a highway bridge sings in the rain they can determine serious flaws in the structure. Employing a method called impact-echo testing, professors Brian Mazzeo and Spencer Guthrie can diagnose the health of a bridge&rsquo;s deck based on the acoustic footprint produced by a little bit of water. <a href="http://news.byu.edu/archive12-oct-bridgesrain.aspx">Read how they do it</a>.</p>
